# Part 1: The Problem — Why Standard Attention Breaks

## 1.1 Softmax Saturation: A Mathematical Deep Dive

The softmax function converts raw scores $z = [z_1, z_2, \dots, z_T]$ into probabilities:

$$\text{softmax}(z_i) = \frac{e^{z_i}}{\sum_{j=1}^T e^{z_j}}$$

The critical property is that softmax is **exponentially sensitive to scale**. Let's prove why this causes attention collapse.

### Theorem: Softmax Converges to One-Hot as Scale Increases

Consider scores $z = [z_1, z_2, \dots, z_T]$ with a unique maximum $z_{\max} = z_k$. Define $\text{gap}_j = z_k - z_j > 0$ for $j \neq k$. Then:

$$\text{softmax}(\beta z)_k = \frac{1}{1 + \sum_{j \neq k} e^{-\beta \cdot \text{gap}_j}} \xrightarrow{\beta \to \infty} 1$$

As $\beta$ (the effective scale/inverse-temperature) grows, softmax converges to a one-hot vector concentrating all mass on the maximum.

### Concrete Demonstration

Take scores $z = [2.0, 1.5, 0.3, 0.1, 0.1]$ (5 tokens, one dominant):

| Scale $\beta$ | softmax($\beta z$) | Entropy $H$ | Max weight |
|---|---|---|---|
| $\beta = 0.5$ | [0.27, 0.24, 0.18, 0.16, 0.16] | 1.58 | 27% |
| $\beta = 1$ | [0.35, 0.21, 0.06, 0.05, 0.05] | 1.28 | 35% |
| $\beta = 2$ | [0.63, 0.14, 0.01, 0.01, 0.01] | 0.71 | 63% |
| $\beta = 5$ | [0.97, 0.008, 0.000, 0.000, 0.000] | 0.09 | 97% |
| $\beta = 10$ | [0.999, ...] | ≈ 0 | 99.9% |

**Entropy** $H = -\sum p_i \log p_i$ measures diversity:
- $H = \log T = \log 5 = 1.61$ → perfectly uniform (max diversity)
- $H = 0$ → one-hot (zero diversity, complete collapse)

> [!WARNING]
> **The hidden danger**: During training, Q and K projections are learned. As the model trains on more data, the learned projections tend to produce **increasingly disparate scores** — the effective $\beta$ grows organically, driving attention toward collapse even without any explicit temperature parameter.

## 1.2 Why Does This Happen During Training?

The scores are $\text{score}_{ij} = \frac{q_i \cdot k_j}{\sqrt{C}}$ where $q_i, k_j \in \mathbb{R}^{d_k}$.

As training progresses:

```
Epoch 1 (random init):
  Q, K weights are small, random
  Scores: [-0.2, 0.1, -0.3, 0.15, 0.05, ...]
  Variance of scores: ~0.04 (small)
  Softmax: [0.013, 0.018, 0.012, 0.019, 0.017, ...]  ← ~uniform

Epoch 10 (partially trained):
  Q, K weights have grown, learned structure
  Scores: [-1.5, 3.2, -0.8, 0.5, -2.1, ...]
  Variance of scores: ~3.5 (growing!)
  Softmax: [0.001, 0.92, 0.002, 0.006, 0.0005, ...]  ← collapsing!

Epoch 50 (well-trained):
  Scores: [-5.2, 12.8, -3.1, 1.2, -7.4, ...]
  Variance of scores: ~45 (very large!)
  Softmax: [0.0, 0.9999, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0, ...]  ← collapsed!
```

The **variance of attention scores grows** because the model learns to discriminate — but softmax converts this discrimination into near-deterministic (one-hot) attention, which is harmful because:

1. **Gradient vanishing**: $\frac{\partial \text{softmax}_i}{\partial z_j} = p_i (\delta_{ij} - p_j)$. When $p_k \approx 1$ and all others $\approx 0$, all partial derivatives $\approx 0$.
2. **Information bottleneck**: Each token's output is essentially just one other token's value — no blending, no context integration.
3. **Representational collapse**: Multiple heads may converge to attending to the same dominant token.

## 1.3 Three Approaches to Fix This

```
The Attention Collapse Problem
         │
    ┌────┴─────────────────────────────────┐
    │                                      │
    ▼                                      ▼
"Fix it AFTER"                      "Prevent it BEFORE"
    │                                      │
    ▼                                      ▼
Differential Attention              MTG Attention
(Code 1)                           (Code 2)
    │                                      │
    ▼                                      ▼
Two softmax maps,                  Standardize scores
subtract them.                     before softmax.
Noise cancels,                     Controls scale,
signal survives.                   prevents saturation.
    │                                      │
    ▼                                      ▼
Cost: 2× Q/K params               Cost: Zero extra params
      + learnable α                      (just mean + var)
```

