# Part 5: Architecture Differences — MTG vs Differential Transformer

## 5.1 Model Architecture Comparison

```
┌─────────────────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────────────────┐
│   Code 1: Differential ViT  │    │    Code 2: MTG ViT           │
│                              │    │                              │
│  PatchEmbed(3→128, k=4)     │    │  PatchEmbed(3→128, k=4)     │
│  [CLS] + PosEmbed           │    │  [CLS] + PosEmbed           │
│  ┌────────────────────────┐  │    │  ┌────────────────────────┐  │
│  │  Block 0 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  │  Block 0 (MTGAttn)     │  │
│  │  Block 1 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  │  Block 1 (MTGAttn)     │  │
│  │  Block 2 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  │  Block 2 (MTGAttn)     │  │
│  │  Block 3 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  │  Block 3 (MTGAttn)     │  │
│  │  Block 4 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  └────────────────────────┘  │
│  │  Block 5 (DiffAttn)    │  │    │  Final LN → CLS → Linear    │
│  └────────────────────────┘  │    │                              │
│  Final LN → CLS → Linear    │    │  Layers: 4                   │
│                              │    │  SR every: 10 steps          │
│  Layers: 6                   │    │                              │
│  SR every: 50 steps          │    │                              │
└─────────────────────────────┘    └─────────────────────────────┘
```

## 5.2 Per-Head Parameter Comparison

| Component | DiffHead | MTGHead | Difference |
|---|---|---|---|
| Query projection(s) | 2 × (128×32) = 8,192 | 1 × (128×32) = 4,096 | DiffHead has 2× |
| Key projection(s) | 2 × (128×32) = 8,192 | 1 × (128×32) = 4,096 | DiffHead has 2× |
| Value projection | 1 × (128×32) = 4,096 | 1 × (128×32) = 4,096 | Same |
| Learnable α | 1 | 0 | DiffHead only |
| MTG normalization | 0 | 0 (no params!) | — |
| **Total per head** | **20,481** | **12,288** | **DiffHead is 67% larger** |

## 5.3 Full Model Parameter Count — MTG ViT

| Component | Parameters | Calculation |
|---|---|---|
| **Patch Embedding** | | |
| Conv2d weights | 6,144 | $3 \times 128 \times 4 \times 4$ |
| Conv2d bias | 128 | 128 output channels |
| **Subtotal** | **6,272** | |
| | | |
| **Special Tokens** | | |
| CLS token | 128 | $1 \times 128$ |
| Positional embedding | 8,320 | $65 \times 128$ |
| **Subtotal** | **8,448** | |
| | | |
| **Per MTG Head** | | |
| W_Q | 4,096 | $128 \times 32$ |
| W_K | 4,096 | $128 \times 32$ |
| W_V | 4,096 | $128 \times 32$ |
| **Subtotal** | **12,288** | |
| | | |
| **Per MultiHeadAttention** | | |
| 4 × MTGHead | 49,152 | $4 \times 12288$ |
| Output proj (weight) | 16,384 | $128 \times 128$ |
| Output proj (bias) | 128 | 128 |
| **Subtotal** | **65,664** | |
| | | |
| **Per FFN** | | |
| Linear1 (weight) | 65,536 | $128 \times 512$ |
| Linear1 (bias) | 512 | |
| Linear2 (weight) | 65,536 | $512 \times 128$ |
| Linear2 (bias) | 128 | |
| **Subtotal** | **131,712** | |
| | | |
| **Per LayerNorm** | | |
| γ (scale) | 128 | |
| β (shift) | 128 | |
| **Subtotal** | **256** | |
| | | |
| **Per LNBlock** | | |
| MHA + FFN + 2×LN | — | 65,664 + 131,712 + 2×256 |
| **Subtotal** | **197,888** | |
| | | |
| **4 Blocks** | **791,552** | $4 \times 197888$ |
| | | |
| **Classification Head** | | |
| Final LayerNorm | 256 | |
| Linear (weight) | 1,280 | $128 \times 10$ |
| Linear (bias) | 10 | |
| **Subtotal** | **1,546** | |
| | | |
| **GRAND TOTAL** | **~807,818** | ≈ 808K parameters |

### Comparison with Differential Transformer

| | Differential ViT (Code 1) | MTG ViT (Code 2) |
|---|---|---|
| Layers | 6 | 4 |
| Params per head (attn) | 20,481 | 12,288 |
| Params per block | ~230K | ~198K |
| **Total parameters** | **~1.4M** | **~808K** |
| **Ratio** | 1.73× larger | baseline |

The MTG model is **42% smaller** — partly from fewer layers (4 vs 6), and partly from single Q/K projections per head instead of double.

---

# Part 6: Training Loop — What's Different

## 6.1 SR Logging Frequency

```python
compute_sr = (step % 10 == 0)    # MTG: every 10 steps
# vs
compute_sr = (step % 50 == 0)    # DiffAttn: every 50 steps
```

**Impact on training data:**

| Metric | Diff. ViT (Code 1) | MTG ViT (Code 2) |
|---|---|---|
| Steps per epoch | ~391 | ~391 |
| Total steps (5 epochs) | ~1,955 | ~1,955 |
| SR data points | ~39 | **~195** |
| SR plot density | Sparse | **5× denser** |
| SVD overhead per step | 0.26% of steps | **10% of steps** |

More frequent SR logging gives smoother, more informative plots but adds SVD computation overhead. Since the MTG model has 4 layers (vs 6), each SR computation involves fewer SVDs, partially offsetting the increased frequency.

**SVD computations per SR step:**
- Code 1: $B \times 2 = 128 \times 2 = 256$ SVDs × 6 layers = 1,536 SVDs every 50 steps
- Code 2: $B \times 2 = 128 \times 2 = 256$ SVDs × 4 layers = 1,024 SVDs every 10 steps

**SVD computations per epoch:**
- Code 1: $\lfloor 391/50 \rfloor \times 1536 \approx 12,000$ SVDs/epoch
- Code 2: $\lfloor 391/10 \rfloor \times 1024 \approx 40,000$ SVDs/epoch

So despite fewer layers, Code 2 does ~3.3× more SVD computation per epoch due to the 5× higher logging frequency.

## 6.2 Per-Layer SR Storage

```python
per_layer_sr_history = [[] for _ in range(n_layer)]    
# Code 1: [[], [], [], [], [], []]    ← 6 lists (6 layers)
# Code 2: [[], [], [], []]            ← 4 lists (4 layers)
```

The per-layer plot will show 4 lines instead of 6.

